\f1\b0\fs44 \cf0 Put some salt on a flat dish. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/moisten/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Moisten}} the rim of the margarita glass with the lime wedge and dip it in to the salt.\
Fill a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cocktail/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cocktail}} shaker with ice. Add the tequila, lime juice, simple syrup and green chile juice to the shaker and shake vigorously for 3 seconds. Pour into the salted glass and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/garnish/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 garnish}} with the lime wedge.\
Cook's Note:\
To make the simple syrup, heat 1 part water and 1 part granulated sugar in a small {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}} until the sugar dissolves. Cool before using.\
To prepare the green chile juice, put 1 New Mexico green chile in a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/blender/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 blender}} with 1 ounce of water and blend thoroughly. Strain the puree through a fine mesh {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/strainer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 strainer}} and transfer to a squeeze bottle. If New Mexico {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/chile/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 green chiles}} are not available, serrano chiles may be substituted.\
